div.p:
Therefore, to announce the gospel with armed forces is utterly alien to the doctrine of Christ, whose whole life and doctrine breathes gentleness and charity. The Lord sent his own to preach the gospel instructed with most pious words:
"Entering a house, he says, "salute it," and say first, peace to this house.
"Behold, I send you as sheep";
"I came that they might have life and have it more abundantly";
"Learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart". But armed forces are suitable to Mohammed the false prophet, who said that he was in the terror of the sword, as has been stated above. The Indians, since they have a probable reason for following the institutions of their ancestors, approved for so many centuries, supported by the authority of so many princes, priests, and learned men among them, are not bound to depart from it at the exhortation of robbers, surpassing all Turks and plunderers in savagery and ferocity. For who would believe that such tyrants are messengers of the true God? Who by their depraved morals defame the gospel and undermine the cause of Christ. Those things please human minds and are inserted into hearts as consonant with reason which are taught by good and trustworthy men. Who, if they have done sensible works conformable to reason— for instance, if they have shown charity, if gentleness, if modesty— will please all, and faith will be given to their words.
